%U A158993 2344883866416,8829641374848,423732883488768
%N A158993 Zeroless numbers m such that m = phi(m/d_1) + phi(m/d_2) + ... + phi(m/d_k), where d_1 d_2 ... d_k is the decimal expansion of m.
%C A158993 It can be shown that any term m > 1 is even, coprime to 5, and thus does not contain digits 0 and 5. Furthermore, for the radical r = rad(m), the denominator of r/phi(r) must divide lcm(1,2,3,4,6,7,8,9) = 2^3*3^2*7, which restricts r to the set of 78 possible values, each of which is the product of 2 and at most 4 odd primes. Heuristically, we expect only a finite number of terms corresponding to each value of r, and thus the sequence is likely finite. There are no other terms below 10^40 suggesting that the sequence is likely complete. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jul 02 2026
%e A158993 211896=phi(211896/2)+phi(211896/1)+phi(211896/1)+phi(211896/8)+phi(211896/9)+phi(211896/6) so 211896 is in the sequence.
%e A158993 eulerphi(16484622336/1)+eulerphi(16484622336/6)+eulerphi(16484622336/4)+eulerphi (16484622336/8)+eulerphi(16484622336/4)+eulerphi(16484622336/6)+eulerphi(1648462 2336/2)+eulerphi(16484622336/2)+eulerphi(16484622336/3)+eulerphi(16484622336/3)+ eulerphi(16484622336/6)=16484622336. - Qu,shun liang (medie2006(AT)126.com), Aug 18 2009
%t A158993 Do[h=IntegerDigits[n];l=Length[h];If[Min[h]>0&&Union[Mod[n,h]]=={0}&&n==Sum[EulerPhi[n/h[[k]]],{k,l}],Print[n]],{n,2000000000}]
